\title{Property Based Testing}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Provides guidance for property-based testing across multiple languages and smart contracts. Use when writing tests, reviewing code with serialization/validation/parsing patterns, designing features, or when property-based testing would provide stronger coverage than example-based tests.}

\subtree{
\title{Property-Based Testing Guide}
\p{Use this skill proactively during development when you encounter patterns where PBT provides stronger coverage than example-based tests.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Invoke (Automatic Detection)}
\p{\strong{Invoke this skill when you detect:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Serialization pairs}: \code{\startverb encode\stopverb}/\code{\startverb decode\stopverb}, \code{\startverb serialize\stopverb}/\code{\startverb deserialize\stopverb}, \code{\startverb toJSON\stopverb}/\code{\startverb fromJSON\stopverb}, \code{\startverb pack\stopverb}/\code{\startverb unpack\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Parsers}: URL parsing, config parsing, protocol parsing, string-to-structured-data}
\li{\strong{Normalization}: \code{\startverb normalize\stopverb}, \code{\startverb sanitize\stopverb}, \code{\startverb clean\stopverb}, \code{\startverb canonicalize\stopverb}, \code{\startverb format\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Validators}: \code{\startverb is_valid\stopverb}, \code{\startverb validate\stopverb}, \code{\startverb check_*\stopverb} (especially with normalizers)}
\li{\strong{Data structures}: Custom collections with \code{\startverb add\stopverb}/\code{\startverb remove\stopverb}/\code{\startverb get\stopverb} operations}
\li{\strong{Mathematical/algorithmic}: Pure functions, sorting, ordering, comparators}
\li{\strong{Smart contracts}: Solidity/Vyper contracts, token operations, state invariants, access control}
}

\p{\strong{Priority by pattern:}}

\pre{\startverb
| Pattern | Property | Priority |
|---------|----------|----------|
| encode/decode pair | Roundtrip | HIGH |
| Pure function | Multiple | HIGH |
| Validator | Valid after normalize | MEDIUM |
| Sorting/ordering | Idempotence + ordering | MEDIUM |
| Normalization | Idempotence | MEDIUM |
| Builder/factory | Output invariants | LOW |
| Smart contract | State invariants | HIGH |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use}
\p{Do NOT use this skill for:}

\ul{
\li{Simple CRUD operations without transformation logic}
\li{One-off scripts or throwaway code}
\li{Code with side effects that cannot be isolated (network calls, database writes)}
\li{Tests where specific example cases are sufficient and edge cases are well-understood}
\li{Integration or end-to-end testing (PBT is best for unit/component testing)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Property Catalog (Quick Reference)}
\pre{\startverb
| Property | Formula | When to Use |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| **Roundtrip** | `decode(encode(x)) == x` | Serialization, conversion pairs |
| **Idempotence** | `f(f(x)) == f(x)` | Normalization, formatting, sorting |
| **Invariant** | Property holds before/after | Any transformation |
| **Commutativity** | `f(a, b) == f(b, a)` | Binary/set operations |
| **Associativity** | `f(f(a,b), c) == f(a, f(b,c))` | Combining operations |
| **Identity** | `f(x, identity) == x` | Operations with neutral element |
| **Inverse** | `f(g(x)) == x` | encrypt/decrypt, compress/decompress |
| **Oracle** | `new_impl(x) == reference(x)` | Optimization, refactoring |
| **Easy to Verify** | `is_sorted(sort(x))` | Complex algorithms |
| **No Exception** | No crash on valid input | Baseline property |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Strength hierarchy} (weakest to strongest): No Exception → Type Preservation → Invariant → Idempotence → Roundtrip}
}

\subtree{
\title{Decision Tree}
\p{Based on the current task, read the appropriate section:}

\pre{\startverb
TASK: Writing new tests
  → Read [{baseDir}/references/generating.md]({baseDir}/references/generating.md) (test generation patterns and examples)
  → Then [{baseDir}/references/strategies.md]({baseDir}/references/strategies.md) if input generation is complex

TASK: Designing a new feature
  → Read [{baseDir}/references/design.md]({baseDir}/references/design.md) (Property-Driven Development approach)

TASK: Code is difficult to test (mixed I/O, missing inverses)
  → Read [{baseDir}/references/refactoring.md]({baseDir}/references/refactoring.md) (refactoring patterns for testability)

TASK: Reviewing existing PBT tests
  → Read [{baseDir}/references/reviewing.md]({baseDir}/references/reviewing.md) (quality checklist and anti-patterns)

TASK: Test failed, need to interpret
  → Read [{baseDir}/references/interpreting-failures.md]({baseDir}/references/interpreting-failures.md) (failure analysis and bug classification)

TASK: Need library reference
  → Read [{baseDir}/references/libraries.md]({baseDir}/references/libraries.md) (PBT libraries by language, includes smart contract tools)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{How to Suggest PBT}
\p{When you detect a high-value pattern while writing tests, \strong{offer PBT as an option}:}

\blockquote{"I notice \code{\startverb encode_message\stopverb}/\code{\startverb decode_message\stopverb} is a serialization pair. Property-based testing with a roundtrip property would provide stronger coverage than example tests. Want me to use that approach?"}

\p{\strong{If codebase already uses a PBT library} (Hypothesis, fast-check, proptest, Echidna), be more direct:}

\blockquote{"This codebase uses Hypothesis. I'll write property-based tests for this serialization pair using a roundtrip property."}

\p{\strong{If user declines}, write good example-based tests without further prompting.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use PBT}
\ul{
\li{Simple CRUD without complex validation}
\li{UI/presentation logic}
\li{Integration tests requiring complex external setup}
\li{Prototyping where requirements are fluid}
\li{User explicitly requests example-based tests only}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Red Flags}
\ul{
\li{Recommending trivial getters/setters}
\li{Missing paired operations (encode without decode)}
\li{Ignoring type hints (well-typed = easier to test)}
\li{Overwhelming user with candidates (limit to top 5-10)}
\li{Being pushy after user declines}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rationalizations to Reject}
\p{Do not accept these shortcuts:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{"Example tests are good enough"} - If serialization/parsing/normalization is involved, PBT finds edge cases examples miss}
\li{\strong{"The function is simple"} - Simple functions with complex input domains (strings, floats, nested structures) benefit most from PBT}
\li{\strong{"We don't have time"} - PBT tests are often shorter than comprehensive example suites}
\li{\strong{"It's too hard to write generators"} - Most PBT libraries have excellent built-in strategies; custom generators are rarely needed}
\li{\strong{"The test failed, so it's a bug"} - Failures require validation; see [interpreting-failures.md]({baseDir}/references/interpreting-failures.md)}
\li{\strong{"No crash means it works"} - "No exception" is the weakest property; always push for stronger guarantees}
}
}
}